subSubSection.paragraph:
Redescription. Male
. Size of body not uniform. Head with fastigium of vertex divided into two evident tubercles, well-divided (
Fig. 2
). Legs slender, fore femur about 1.7 times long as pronotum, fore femur beneath with spines, external genicular lobe with 1 long movable spine, internal genicular lobe with 1 small spine (
Fig. 3
); fore tibiae beneath with 2 external spines and 1 internal spine, between the apical paired spines with a short spine. Mid femur with 1 external and 1 internal genicular spine separately; mid tibiae beneath with 1 external spine and 1 internal spine, between the apical paired spines with 1 small spine. Hind femur beneath with 4–9 internal spines, without external spine; hind tibiae with 64–70 spines, arrange in groups, 1 group comprise 3–7 spines (
Fig. 5
), the longest apical spine situated in internal side of hind tibiae almost equal or slightly longer than apex of hind metatarsus. Hind metatarsus keeled beneath and with 1 apical spine dorsally. Epiproct nearly rectangular, its long about 1.5 times as wide, hind margin concave, middle part of lateral margin convex, almost blunt (
Fig. 4
). Male genitalia with dorsolateral lobes inflated and sclerotized heavily, apex undivided, middle lobe rather short and small, pseudosternite small, upper apex with 1 small incision (
Fig. 7
).

Female
. Ovipositor slightly shorter than half of hind femur, apical part of ventral valvula serrated (
Fig. 6
). Subgenital plate nearly trapezoid, apex of hind margin with 1 small projection (
Fig. 8
).
